<paper id="1683242238"><title>Cryptanalysis of a voting scheme</title><year>1997</year><authors><author org="University of Technology Chemnitz-Zwickau" id="2101606628">Markus Michels</author><author org="University of Technology Chemnitz-Zwickau" id="2559256607">Patrick Horster</author></authors><n_citation>2</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1479744988</reference><reference>1541330898</reference><reference>2103647628</reference><reference>2108834246</reference><reference>2912577494</reference></references><venue id="1130451194" type="C">International Conference on Communications</venue><doi>10.1007/978-0-387-35083-7_5</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.52902">Voting</keyword><keyword weight="0.45475">Computer security</keyword><keyword weight="0.53848">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.44414">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.54845">Cryptanalysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.43256">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.61739">Linear cryptanalysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.51616">Anonymity</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Boston, MA</publisher><abstract>At Eurocrypt’93 Park, Itoh and Kurusawa presented a voting scheme based on an efficient concrete mix-net. However, Pfitzmann pointed out that the used concrete mix-net is vulnerable to active and passive attacks. Therefore, the anonymity of the votes can’t be guaranteed. Furthermore, Pfitzmann discussed some countermeasures against the attacks and how far they help.</abstract></paper>